# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-history
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The **10th millennium BC** spanned the years 10,000 BC to 9001 BC (c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] It marks the beginning of the transition from the Palaeolithic to the Neolithic via the interim Mesolithic (Northern Europe and Western Europe) and Epipaleolithic (Levant and Near East) periods, which together form the first part of the Holocene epoch that is generally believed to have begun c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 11.7 ka) and is the current geological epoch.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] It is impossible to precisely date events that happened around the time of this millennium, and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological analysis, anthropological analysis, and radiometric dating.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The main characteristic of the Holocene has been the worldwide abundance of *Homo sapiens sapiens* (humankind).
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The epoch began in the wake of the Würm glaciation, generally known as the Last Ice Age, which began 109 ka and ended 14 ka, when *Homo sapiens sapiens* was in the Palaeolithic (Old Stone) Age.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Following the Late Glacial Interstadial from 14 ka to 12.9 ka, during which global temperatures rose significantly, the Younger Dryas began.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] This was a temporary reversal of climatic warming to glacial conditions in the Northern Hemisphere and coincided with the end of the Upper Palaeolithic.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 9700 BC, marking the cutover from Pleistocene to Holocene.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] In the geologic time scale, there are three (tentatively four) stratigraphic stages of the Holocene beginning c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The starting point for the Greenlandian is the Global Boundary Stratotype Section and Point (GSSP) sample from the North Greenland Ice Core Project, which has been correlated with the Younger Dryas.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Greenlandian was succeeded by the "Northgrippian" (to c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] All three stages were officially ratified by the International Commission on Stratigraphy in July 2018.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] It has been proposed that the Meghalayan should be terminated c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 1950 and succeeded by a new stage provisionally called "Anthropocene".
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] In the Holocene's first millennium, the Palaeolithic began to be superseded by the Neolithic (New Stone) Age which lasted about 6,000 years, depending on location.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The gradual transition period is sometimes termed Mesolithic (northern and western Europe) or Epipalaeolithic (Levant and Near East).
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The glaciers retreated as the world climate became warmer and that inspired an agricultural revolution, though at first, the dog was probably the only domesticated animal.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] This was accompanied by a social revolution in that humans gained from agriculture the impetus to settle.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Settlement is the key precursor to civilisation, which cannot be achieved by a nomadic lifestyle.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 10,000 BC, is believed to have been more or less stable.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] It has been estimated that there were some five million people at the time of the Last Glacial Maximum, growing to forty million by 5000 BC and 100 million by 1600 BC, which is an average growth rate of 0.027% p.a. from the Neolithic to the Middle Bronze Age.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Around 10,000 BC, most people lived in hunter-gatherer communities scattered across all continents except Antarctica and Zealandia.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] As the Würm/Wisconsin ended, settlement of northern regions was again possible.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Agriculture developed in different parts of the world at different times.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] In many places, people learned how to cultivate without outside help; elsewhere, as in western Europe, the skills were imported.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] A decrease in human height accompanied the rise of agriculture near the start of the Holocene period (10,000 BC) and was later correlated with urban population density.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Natufian culture prevailed in the Levant through the 10th millennium and was unusual in that it supported a sedentary or semi-sedentary population even before the introduction of agriculture.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] An early example is 'Ain Mallaha, which may have been the first village in which people were wholly sedentary.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Natufian people are believed to have founded another early settlement on the site of Jericho (Tell es-Sultan) where there is evidence of building between 9600 BC and 8200 BC.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Dates for the Natufian are indeterminate and range broadly from c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] It is possible that the early cultivation of figs began in the Jordan River valley sometime after the middle of the 10th millennium.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Besides the fig trees, the people may have begun cultivation of wild plants such as barley and pistachio; and they possibly began herding goats, pigs and cattle.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Agriculture began to be developed by the various communities of the Fertile Crescent, which included the Levant, but it would not be widely practised for another 2,000 years by which time Neolithic culture was becoming well established in many parts of the Near East.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Among the earliest cultivated plants were forms of millet and rice grown in the Middle East, possibly in this millennium but more likely after 9000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] By about 9500 BC, people in south-eastern Anatolia were harvesting wild grasses and grains.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The earliest evidence of sheep herding has been found in northern Iraq, dated before 9000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Prehistoric chronology is almost entirely reliant upon the dating of material objects of which pottery is by far the most widespread and the most resistant to decay.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] All locations and generations developed their own shapes, sizes and styles of pottery, including methods and styles of decoration, but there was consistency among stratified deposits and even shards can be classified by time and place.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Pottery is believed to have been discovered independently in various places, beginning with China c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 18,000 BC, and was probably created accidentally by fires lit on clay soil.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The main discovery of pottery dated to the 10th millennium has been at Bosumpra Cave (early tenth-millennium cal.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] BC) on the Kwahu Plateau in southeastern Ghana and Ounjougou (c.9400 BC) in Central Mali, providing evidence of an independent invention of pottery in Sub-Saharan Africa in different climatic zones.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The first chronological pottery system was the Early, Middle and Late Minoan framework devised in the early 20th century by Sir Arthur Evans for his findings at Knossos.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] This covered the Bronze Age in twelve phases from c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 1050 BC and the principle was later extended to mainland Greece (Helladic) and the Aegean islands (Cycladic).
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Dame Kathleen Kenyon was the principal archaeologist at Tell es-Sultan (ancient Jericho) and she discovered that there was no pottery there.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The potter's wheel had not yet been invented and, where pottery as such was made, it was still hand-built, often by means of coiling, and pit fired.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Kenyon discovered vessels such as bowls, cups, and plates at Jericho which were made from stone.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] She reasonably surmised that others made from wood or vegetable fibres would have long since decayed.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Using Evans' system as a benchmark, Kenyon divided the Near East Neolithic into phases called Pre-Pottery Neolithic A (PPNA), from c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 8800 BC; Pre-Pottery Neolithic B (PPNB), from c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 6500 BC; and then Pottery Neolithic (PN), which had varied start-points from c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 6500 BC until the beginnings of the Bronze Age towards the end of the 4th millennium.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] In the 10th millennium, the Natufian culture co-existed with the PPNA which prevailed in the Levantine and upper Mesopotamian areas of the Fertile Crescent.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] In North Africa, Saharan rock art engravings in what is known as the Bubalus (Large Wild Fauna) period have been dated to between 10,000 BC and 7000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Wall paintings found in Ethiopia and Eritrea depict human activity; some of the older paintings are thought to date back to around 10,000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] In Prehistoric Egypt, a culture of hunter-gatherers replaced a grain grinding culture in 10,000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Abu Madi tel mounds in the Sinai Peninsula have been dated c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Clovis culture was widely distributed throughout North America.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The people were hunter-gatherers and the culture's duration is believed to have been from c.9050 BC to c.8800 BC.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] There is evidence of increasing use of Clovis point tool technology for hunting.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Elsewhere in North America, the Petroglyphs at Winnemucca Lake, in what is today northwest Nevada, were carved by this time, possibly as early as 12.8 ka or as late as 10 ka.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The sites at Göbekli Tepe, which is home to megalithic structures, Hallan Çemi Tepesi, both in south-eastern Anatolia, and at Tell Qaramel, in north-west Syria, may have been occupied during this millennium.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] It was found out that gastronomy first emerged in Göbekli Tepe in this millennium.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] This most important discovery shedding light on the beginning of gastronomy in Anatolia consists of religious places in which feasts were held in this millennium that were found in the archaeological excavations conducted in Göbekli Tepe in Urfa province which is called the zero point of time.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Sassi di Matera in southern Italy is believed to have been the site of human settlement since the Paleolithic period in this millennium, making it one of the oldest continuously inhabited settlements in history.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] At the Hasankeyf Mound in Turkey, Europe, almost all archaeological data date to this millennium.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] In Great Britain, which was not then an island, the Star Carr site in North Yorkshire is believed to have been inhabited by Maglemosian peoples for about 800 years from c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Bhimbetka rock shelters, which feature prehistoric cave paintings, earliest being dated to 10,000 BCE, corresponds to the Indian Mesolithic.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] These sites would have been home to a nomadic/hunting society existing in this region.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] In the southern hemisphere, rising sea levels had gradually formed Bass Strait, separating Tasmania from mainland Australia.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] This process is believed to have been complete by about the beginning of the 10th millennium.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Bass Strait had been a plain populated by indigenous people who are thought to have first arrived around 40,000 years ago.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Wisconsin glaciation had sheeted much of North America and, as it retreated, its meltwaters created an immense proglacial lake now known as Lake Agassiz.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Sometime after 10,000 BC, the retreating glaciers created the rock formation on Cannon Mountain in present-day New Hampshire that was known as the Old Man of the Mountain until its collapse in 2003.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The ongoing Quaternary System/Period represents the last 2.58 million years since the end of the Neogene and is officially divided into the Pleistocene and Holocene Series/Epochs.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Holocene has been assigned an age of 11,700 calendar years before 2000 CE which means it began c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] It is preceded in the geological time scale by the Late Pleistocene sub-epoch, also known as the Tarantian Stage/Age, which awaits formal ratification by the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) and tentatively spans the time from c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] Preceding the Late Pleistocene is the Middle Pleistocene sub-epoch, or Chibanian Stage/Age, which also awaits ratification and tentatively spans the time from c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] 773,000 is sub-divided into two Stages/Ages which have been officially defined: the Gelasian (until c.
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Holocene calendar, devised by Cesare Emiliani in 1993, places its epoch at 10,000 BC (with the year 2026 being rendered as 12026 HE).
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] The Human Era calendar attempts to simplify the calculation of time spans across the BC-CE divide by designating a more universally relevant epoch date: the start of human settlements (instead of the birth of Jesus Christ).
[src:ancient-history/10-000-bce] CE dates can be converted by adding 10,000 years; converting BC dates requires subtraction from 10,001 (since the Gregorian calendar lacks a year zero).
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The religions of this set share doctrinal, historical, and geographic overlap that contrast them with Indian religions, Iranian religions, and East Asian religions, although some smaller Abrahamic religions, such as the Baha'i Faith, are also Iranian religions.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, are the three largest Abrahamic religions, with Christianity and Islam being followed and adhered to by around half of the world's population.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] However, the term has been criticized by some scholars for reportedly oversimplifying cultural and doctrinal nuances between the different religions.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The term *Abrahamic religions* (and its variations) is a collective religious descriptor for similar and closely related elements shared by Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, as well as the smaller religions such as the Baháʼí Faith, the Druze faith, Rastafari, and Samaritanism.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] It features prominently in interfaith dialogue and civil discourse, as well as academic discourse.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The term appears for the first time in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Although historically the term *Abrahamic religions* was limited to just Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, restricting the category to these three religions has come under criticism.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The late-19th-century Baháʼí Faith has been characterized as Abrahamic, as it is a monotheistic religion that recognizes its own descent from Abraham.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The figure of Abraham is suggested as a common ground for Judaism, Christianity, Islam, as well as Samaritanism, the Druze Faith, the Baha'i Faith, and Rastafari and a hypothesized eschatological reconciliation of the seven religions.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Commonalities may include creation, revelation, and redemption, but such shared concepts vary significantly between and within the Abrahamic religions themselves.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Proponents of the term argue that all seven religions are united through the deity worshipped by Abraham.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The Catholic scholar of Islam Louis Massignon argued that the phrase "Abrahamic religion" means that the religions come from one spiritual source.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The modern term comes from the plural form of a Quranic reference to *dīn Ibrāhīm* ("religion of Abraham").
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In Christianity, Paul the Apostle, in Romans 4:11–12, refers to Abraham as "father of all", including those "who have faith, circumcised or uncircumcised." From its founding, Islam likewise conceived of itself as the "religion of Abraham".
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The Bahá’í scriptures state that the religion's founder, Baháʼu'lláh, descended from Abraham through his wife Keturah's sons.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The appropriateness of grouping Judaism, Christianity, and Islam as "Abrahamic religions" and related terms has been challenged.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Adam Dodds argues that the term "Abrahamic faiths", while helpful, can be misleading, as it conveys an unspecified historical and theological commonality that is problematic on closer examination.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] While there is commonality among the religions, their shared ancestry is mainly peripheral to their respective foundational theological claims, practices, and cultures, concealing irreconcilable differences.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The common Christian doctrines of Jesus's Incarnation, the Trinity, and the resurrection of Jesus, for example, are accepted in neither Judaism nor Islam.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Jewish tradition claims that the Twelve Tribes of Israel are descended from Abraham through his son Isaac and grandson Jacob, whose sons formed the nation of the Israelites in Canaan.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In its early stages, the Israelite religion (Yahwism) shares traits with the Canaanite religions of the Bronze Age; by the Iron Age, it had become distinct from other Canaanite religions as it shed polytheism for monolatry.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] They understood their relationship with their god, Yahweh, as a covenant and that the deity promised Abraham a permanent homeland.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The monolatrist nature of Yahwism was further developed in the period following the Babylonian captivity, eventually emerging as a firm religious movement of monotheism.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] With the Fall of Babylon, Judaism incorporated concepts such as messianism, belief in free will and judgement after death, conception of heaven and hell, angels and demons, among others, into their belief-system.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Christianity traces back their origin to the 1st century and refers to themselves as a continuation of Judaism (commonly referred to as the old covenant) initially led by Jesus.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] His followers viewed him as the Messiah, as in the Confession of Peter; after his crucifixion and death they came to view him as God incarnate, who was resurrected and will return at the end of time to judge the living and the dead and create an eternal Kingdom of God.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In the 1st century AD, under the Apostles of Jesus of Nazareth; Christianity spread widely.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Paul the Apostle interpreted the role of Abraham differently from the Jews of his time.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] While for the Jews, Abraham was considered a loyal monotheist in a polytheistic environment, Paul celebrates Abraham as a man who found faith in God before adhering to religious law.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In contrast to Judaism, adherence to religious law becomes associated with idolatry.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] While Christians fashioned their religion around Jesus of Nazareth, the siege of Jerusalem (70 CE), forced Jews to reconcile their belief-system with the destruction of the Second Temple and associated rituals.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] At this time, both Judaism and Christianity had to systematize their scriptures and beliefs, resulting in competing theologies both claiming Abrahamic heritage.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Christians could hardly dismiss the Hebrew scriptures as Jesus himself refers to them according to Christian reports, and parallels between Jesus and the Biblical stories of *creation* and *redemption* starting with Abraham in the *Book of Genesis*.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The distant God asserted by Jesus according to the Christians, created a form of dualism between Creator and creation and the doctrine of *Creatio ex nihilo*, which later heavily influenced Jewish and Islamic theology.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] By that, Christians established their own identity, distinct from both Greeks and Jews, as those who venerate and worship the deity of Jesus.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] After several periods of alternating persecution and relative peace *vis-à-vis* the Roman authorities under different administrations, Christianity became the state church of the Roman Empire in 380, but has been split into various churches from its beginning.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] An attempt was made by the Byzantine Empire to unify Christendom, but this formally failed with the East–West Schism of 1054.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In the 16th century, the birth and growth of Protestantism during the Reformation further split Christianity into many denominations.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Christianity remains culturally diverse in its Western and Eastern branches, Christianity played a prominent role in the development of Western civilization.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Islam is based on the teachings of the Quran.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Although it considers Muhammad to be the Seal of the prophets, Islam teaches that every prophet preached Islam, as the word *Islam* means submission, the main concept preached by all prophets.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The Quran also mentions God having revealed the Scrolls of Abraham and the Scrolls of Moses.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Islamic tradition claims that twelve Arab tribes known as the Ishmaelites are descended from Abraham through his son Ishmael in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The relationship between Islamic and Hebrew scriptures and New Testament differs significantly from the relationship between the New Testament and the Hebrew Bible.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In the 7th century AD, Islam was founded by Muhammad in the Arabian Peninsula; it spread widely through the early Muslim conquests, shortly after his death.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Islam understands its form of "Abrahamic monotheism" as preceding both Judaism and Christianity, and in contrast with Arabian Henotheism.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The teachings of the Quran are believed by Muslims to be the direct and final revelation and words of God.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Islam, like Christianity, is a universal religion (i.e. membership is open to anyone).
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Like Judaism, it has a strictly unitary conception of God, called *tawhid* or "strict monotheism".
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The story of the creation of the world in the Quran is elaborated less extensively than in the Hebrew scripture, emphasizing the transcendence and universality of God, instead.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] According to the Quran, God says *kun fa-yakūnu*.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The Quran describes God as the creator of "heavens and earth", to emphasize that it is a universal God and not a local Arabian deity.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Samaritanism is considered by some fringe Jewish and Christian apologetics to be a sect which diverged from Judaism in the 6th to 3rd centuries BCE.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] There is growing archaeological, DNA testing, and textual evidence in modern times which has proved the status of the Israelite Samaritans as an independent Abrahamic ethnoreligion and indigenous people of the Levant in their own right.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The evidence has authenticated their claim to a legal religious status.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Some sources consider Mandaeism to be an Abrahamic religion – however, that classification is controversial, given that Mandaeism does not accept Abraham as a prophet, despite revering as prophets several other figures from the Jewish scriptures.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] On the contrary, the Mandaeans believe that Abraham was originally a priest of their religion, but became an apostate from it.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Druze is another religion which emerged from Islam in the 11th century, and hence is sometimes also considered an Abrahamic religion.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Yazidism, another Kurdish religion, is considered a syncretic religion and shares elements with Shia Islam, Mandaeism, Christianity, and Judaism, including a belief in Adam and Abraham.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] It has also been influenced by Islamic mysticism and Gnostic Christianity.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In Yazidism, the prophet Abraham is invoked during prayers before a meal, especially ritual meals.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] A number of sources include the Baháʼí Faith, established in the 19th century, since it historically emerged in an Islamic milieu, and shares several beliefs with the Abrahamic faiths, including monotheism and recognising Jewish, Christian and Islamic figures as prophets.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Some scholars include Bábism, a 19th-century movement and precursor to the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Rastafari, an Afrocentric religion which emerged from Christianity in 1930s Jamaica, is also sometimes classified as Abrahamic, in particular due to its monotheism and use of the Bible as scripture.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Abrahamic religions agree upon the createdness of the universe by God, who is conceived of as eternal, omnipotent, and omniscient.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] All three identify the creator of the universe with the God revealed to Abraham.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] However, they differ on how to conceptualize God.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Christianity proposes God's utter transcendence and that an intermediary — such as an incarnation of God — is required to bridge the gap between God and humans.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] According to Islam, God is knowable through his creation, metaphorical stories of the prophets stored in the Quran, and signs in nature.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Christianity proposes God's personhood in the form of a Son of God as an aspect of the Divinity as formulated in the doctrine of the Trinity.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In contrast, God in Islam is less personal than described in the Judeo-Christian tradition, and more of a mysterious power behind all aspects of the universe.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Their religious texts feature many of the same figures, histories, and places, although they often present them with different roles, perspectives, and meanings.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Believers who agree on these similarities and the common Abrahamic origin tend to also be more positive towards other Abrahamic groups.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Religious law in Judaism and Samaritanism commands that males be circumcised when they are eight days old, as does the *sunnah* ('tradition') in Islam.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Despite its common practice in Muslim-majority nations, circumcision is considered to be *sunnah* and not required for a life directed by Allah.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Although there is some debate within Islam over whether it is a religious requirement or mere recommendation, circumcision (called *khitan*) is practiced nearly universally by Muslim males.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Today, many Christian denominations are neutral about ritual male circumcision, neither requiring it for religious observance nor forbidding it for cultural or other reasons.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Western Christianity replaced the custom of male circumcision with the ritual of baptism, a ceremony which varies according to the doctrine of the denomination, but it generally includes immersion, aspersion, or anointment with water.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The Early Church, as recorded in Acts 15 at the Council of Jerusalem, decided that Gentile Christians are not required to undergo circumcision.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The Council of Florence in the 15th century prohibited it.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Paragraph #2297 of the Catechism of the Catholic Church calls non-medical amputation or mutilation immoral.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] By the 21st century, the Catholic Church had adopted a neutral position on the practice, as long as it was not practised as an initiation ritual.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Catholic scholars make various arguments in support of the idea that this policy is not in contradiction with the previous edicts.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The New Testament, in Acts 15, records that Christianity did not require circumcision.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Coptic Christians practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The Eritrean Orthodox Church and the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church calls for circumcision, with near-universal prevalence among Orthodox men in Ethiopia.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Many countries with majorities of Christian adherents in Europe and Latin America have low circumcision rates.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In contrast, both religious and non-religious circumcision is widely practiced in many predominantly Christian countries and among Christian communities in the Anglosphere countries, Oceania, South Korea, the Philippines, the Middle East and Africa.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Countries such as the United States, the Philippines, Australia (albeit primarily in the older generations), Canada, Cameroon, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Equatorial Guinea, Ghana, Nigeria, Kenya, and many other African Christian countries have high circumcision rates.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Circumcision is near universal in the Christian countries of Oceania.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In some African and Eastern Christian denominations male circumcision is an integral or established practice, and require that their male members undergo circumcision.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Coptic Christianity and Ethiopian Orthodoxy and Eritrean Orthodoxy still observe male circumcision and practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Male circumcision is also widely practiced among Christians from Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Palestine, Israel, and North Africa.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Male circumcision is among the rites of Islam and is part of the *fitrah*, or the innate disposition and natural character and instinct of the human creation.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Although circumcision is widely practiced among the Druze, it is performed as a cultural tradition and has no religious significance in the Druze faith.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Some Druze do not circumcise their male children, and refuse to observe this "common Muslim practice".
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Circumcision is not a religious practice of the Bahá'í Faith, and the decision is left to the parents.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Judaism accepts converts, but has had no explicit missionaries since the end of the Second Temple period.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Judaism states that non-Jews can achieve righteousness by following Noahide Laws, a set of moral imperatives that, according to the Talmud, were given by God as a binding set of laws for the "children of Noah"—that is, all of humanity.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] It is believed that as much as 10% of the Roman Empire followed Judaism either as fully ritually obligated Jews or the simpler rituals required of non-Jewish members of that faith.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In the U.S., as of 2003, 28% of married Jews were married to non-Jews.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Many Christian organizations, especially Protestant churches, send missionaries to non-Christian communities throughout the world.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Forced conversions to Catholicism have happened at various points throughout history.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Forced conversions to Protestantism has occurred as well, notably during the Reformation, especially in England and Ireland (see recusancy and Popish plot).
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Forced conversions are now condemned as sinful by major denominations such as the Roman Catholic Church, which officially states that forced conversions pollute the Christian religion and offend human dignity, so that past or present offences are regarded as a scandal (a cause of unbelief).
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] According to Pope Paul VI, "It is one of the major tenets of Catholic doctrine that man's response to God in faith must be free: no one, therefore, is to be forced to embrace the Christian faith against his own will." The Roman Catholic Church has declared that Catholics should fight anti-Semitism.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Islam encourages proselytism in various forms.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Dawah is an important Islamic concept that denotes the preaching of Islam.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Da‘wah literally means "issuing a summons" or "making an invitation".
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] A Muslim who practices da‘wah, either as a religious worker or in a volunteer community effort, is called a dā‘ī, plural du‘āt.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] A dā‘ī is thus a person who invites people to understand Islam through a dialogical process and may be categorized in some cases as the Islamic equivalent of a missionary, as one who invites people to the faith, to the prayer, or to Islamic life.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Some pursue Islamic studies specifically to perform Da'wah.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Mosques and other Islamic centers sometimes actively spread Da'wah, similar to evangelical churches.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Others consider being open to the public and answering questions to be Da'wah.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Recalling Muslims to the faith and expanding their knowledge can also be considered Da'wah.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] In Islamic theology, the purpose of Da'wah is to invite people, both Muslims and non-Muslims, to understand the commandments of God as expressed in the Quran and the Sunnah of the Prophet, as well as to inform them about Muhammad.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Da'wah produces converts to Islam, which in turn grows the size of the Muslim Ummah, or community of Muslims.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] While there were instances of forced conversions to Islam, these were neither the norm nor part of a systematic strategy of expansion.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Many Muslim rulers practiced religious pluralism, and the Quran explicitly prohibits compulsion in matters of faith.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Most conversions to Islam occurred gradually, driven by social, cultural, and economic influences rather than coercion.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] However, forcible conversion continues to be practiced in parts of the Islamic world.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Christianity is the largest Abrahamic religion with about 2.5 billion adherents, called Christians, constituting about 31.1% of the world's population.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] Islam is the second largest Abrahamic religion, as well as the fastest-growing Abrahamic religion in recent decades.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] It has about 2.0 billion adherents, called Muslims, constituting about 24.1% of the world's population.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The third largest Abrahamic religion is Judaism with about 14.1 million adherents, called Jews.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The Baháʼí Faith has over 8 million adherents, making it the fourth largest Abrahamic religion, and the fastest growing religion across the 20th century, usually at least twice the rate of population growth.
[src:ancient-history/abrahamic-religion] The Druze faith has between one million and nearly two million adherents.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:ancient-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] An **acropolis** was the settlement of an upper part of an ancient Greek city, especially a citadel, and frequently a hill with precipitous sides, mainly chosen for purposes of defense.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The term is typically used to refer to the Acropolis of Athens, yet nearly every Greek city had an acropolis of its own.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The term derives from the homonymous Greek word "Ακρόπολις", composed from "akron" (ἄκρον), which means "top", and "polis" (πόλις), which means "city".
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Acropolises were used as religious centers and places of worship, forts, and places in which the royal and high-status resided.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Acropolises became the nuclei of large cities of classical ancient times, and served as important centers of a community.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Some well-known acropolises have become the centers of tourism in the present day, and they are a rich source of archaeological information of ancient Greece, especially, the Acropolis of Athens.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The plural of *acropolis* (ακρόπολη) is *acropolises*, also commonly as *acropoleis* and *acropoles*, and ακροπόλεις in Greek.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The term acropolis is also used to describe the central complex of overlapping structures, such as plazas and pyramids, in many Mayan cities, including Tikal and Copán.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Acropolis is also the term used by archaeologists and historians for the urban Castro culture settlements located in Northwestern Iberian hilltops.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] It is primarily associated with the Greek cities of Athens, Argos (with Larisa), Thebes (with Cadmea), Corinth (with its Acrocorinth), and Rhodes (with its Acropolis of Lindos).
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] It may also be applied generically to all such citadels including Rome, Carthage, Jerusalem, Celtic Bratislava, Asia Minor, or Castle Rock in Edinburgh.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] An example in Ireland is the Rock of Cashel.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] In Central Italy, many small rural communes still cluster at the base of a fortified habitation known as *rocca* of the commune.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Other parts of the world have developed other names for the high citadel, or *alcázar*, which often have reinforced a naturally strong site.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Because of this, many cultures have included acropolises in their societies; however, they do not use the same name for them.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The acropolis of a city was used in many ways, with regard to ancient time and through references.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Because an acropolis was built at the highest part of a city, it served as a highly functional form of protection, a fortress, and was as well as a home to the royal of a city and a centre for religion through the worshipping of different gods.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] There have been many classical and ancient acropolises, including the most commonly-known, Acropolis of Athens, as well as the Tepecik Acropolis at Patara, Ankara Acropolis, Acropolis of La Blanca, Acropolis at the Maya Site in Guatemala, and the Acropolis at Halieis.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The most famous example is the Athenian Acropolis, which is a collection of structures featuring a citadel on the highest part of land in ancient (and modern-day) Athens, Greece.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Many notable structures at the site were constructed in the 5th century BCE, including the Propylaea, Erechtheion, and the Temple of Athena.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The Temple is also commonly known as the Parthenon, which is derived from the divine Athena Parthenos.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] There were often dances, music and plays held at the acropolis, which it served as a community centre for the city of Athens.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] It became a prime tourist destination by the 2nd century AD during the Roman Empire and was known as "the Greece of Greece," as coined by an unknown poet.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Although originating in the mainland of Greece, use of the acropolis model quickly spread to Greek colonies such as the Dorian Lato on Crete during the Archaic Period.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The Tepecik Acropolis at Patara served as a harbor to nearby communities and naval forces, such as Antigonos I Monopthalmos and Demetrios Poliorketes, and combined land and sea.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Its fortification wall and Bastion date back to the Classical period.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The acropolis was constructed in the fourth century BCE by the Hekatomnids that ultimately led to its seizure in 334 BCE by Alexander the Great.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The acropolis contributed significantly to the overall development that took place during the Hellenistic empires.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] This acropolis was the earliest place of settlement, probably dating back to the third millennium BCE.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] During excavations that took place in 1989, ceramic items, terracotta figurines, coins, bone and stone objects were found that date to the fourth century BCE.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The fortification wall and bastion that are built at this acropolis uses a style of masonry, commonly known as the Greek word ἔμπλεκτον (meaning "woven").
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] This style of masonry was likely used for weight-bearing purposes.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The Acropolis at Halieis dates back to the Neolithic and Classical periods.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] It included a fortified wall, sanctuary of Apollo (two temples, an altar, a race course), and necropolis (cemetery).
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] This acropolis was the highest point of fortification on the south edge at Halieis.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] There was a small open-air cult space, including an altar and monuments.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The Ankara Acropolis, which was set in modern-day Turkey, is a historically prominent space that has changed over time through the urban development of the country from the Phrygian period.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] This acropolis was well known as a spot for holy worshipping, and was symbolic of the time.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] It has also been a place that has historically recognized the legislative changes that Turkey has faced.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The Acropolis of La Blanca was created in Guatemala as a small ancient Maya settlement and archaeological site that is located adjacent to the Salsipuedes River.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] This acropolis developed as a place of residence for the city of La Blanca's rulers.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Its main period of usage was during the Classical period of 600 AD to 850 AD, as the city developed as a commercial place of trade among a number of nearby settlements.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The Mayan Acropolis site in Guatemala included a burial site and vaulted tombs of the highest status royal.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] This funerary structure was integrated into this sacred landscape, and illustrated the prosperity of power between the royal figures of Pedras Negras in Guatemala.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Acropolises today have become the epicenters of tourism and attraction sites in many modern-day Greek cities.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The Athenian Acropolis, in particular, is the most famous, and has the best vantage point in Athens, Greece.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Today, tourists can purchase tickets to visit the Athenian Acropolis, including walking, sightseeing, and bus tours, as well as a classic Greek dinner.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Because of its classical Hellenistic and Greco-Roman style, the ruins of Mission San Juan Capistrano's Great Stone Church in California, United States has been called an American Acropolis.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The civilization developed its religious, educational, and cultural aspects of the acropolis, and is used today as a location that holds events, such as operas.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The analogy is also aided by the neoclassical architecture of the Columbia University campus, which was designed by McKim, Mead & White in the early 20th century.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Much of the modern-day uses of acropolises have been discovered through excavations that have developed over the course of many years.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] For example, the Athenian Acropolis includes a Great Temple that holds the Parthenon, a specific space for ancient worship.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Through today's findings and research, the Parthenon treasury is able to be recognized as the west part of the structure (the Erechtheion), as well as the Parthenon itself.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] Most excavations have been able to provide archaeologists with samples of pottery, ceramics, and vessels.
[src:ancient-history/acropolis] The excavation of the Acropolis of Halieis produced remains that provided context that dated the Acropolis at Halieis from the Final Neolithic period through the first Early Helladic period.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] Hart-Davis was awarded an Honorary Fellowship of the Royal Photographic Society in 2007.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] Hart-Davis was born and brought up in Henley-on-Thames, the youngest child of the publisher Sir Rupert Hart-Davis (1907–1999) and his second wife, Catherine Comfort Borden-Turner.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] He was educated at St Andrew's Preparatory School, near Pangbourne, and then at Eton College, before reading chemistry at Merton College, Oxford.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] He then took a PhD degree in organometallic chemistry at the University of York and spent three years as a post-doctoral scholar at the University of Alberta in Canada.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] Subsequently, he worked at the Oxford University Press, editing science texts and chess manuals.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] In 2004 he was awarded an honorary degree (Doctor of Letters) from the University of Bath.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] Hart-Davis's work in broadcasting began in 1977 when he joined Yorkshire Television (YTV) as a researcher, working on material for Magnus Pyke, David Bellamy, Miriam Stoppard as well as *Arthur C.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] In 1985 he was promoted to production work, producing the Fred Harris-fronted TV show *Me & My Micro* and the Johnny Ball-fronted *Fun & Games*, amongst other things.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] He also devised and produced the school science show *Scientific Eye*.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] In the early 1990s Hart-Davis moved in front of the camera to present two series for YTV: *On The Edge* and *Local Heroes*.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] The latter programme featured him cycling around the North of England in his trademark fluorescent pink and yellow cycling clothes, seeking out places associated with the great innovators of science and technology.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] The bicycles were his own, as he is a keen cyclist, owning an early Burrows Windcheetah as well as a mountain bike fitted with an early front monoblade.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] This series was transferred to BBC2, where its scope became national, a different region being the subject of each episode.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] *Big Questions*, a five-part Channel 4 science series for young people that he presented received a BAFTA nomination in 2002.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] A new television series for the BBC called *The Cosmos – A Beginner's Guide* was broadcast on 7 August 2007 by BBC Two, and explored the latest ideas and experiments in cosmology.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] It was accompanied by a book of the same name.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] He also appeared in TV advertisements for HM Revenue & Customs with the catchphrase "tax doesn't have to be taxing".
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] Following a statement from Hart-Davis, in which he mentioned the level of complexities within the UK tax system, his contract with HM Revenue & Customs ended.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] Hart-Davis has a passion for raising awareness of simple benefits that science may bring to the quality of living, particularly in the developing world.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] One such innovation is the design of smoke-hoods from galvanised iron or mud to prevent the deadly effects of smoke inhalation from cooking fires inside houses in the developing world.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] He is the Patron of the FatallyFlawed campaign against the use of plug-in socket covers.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] He is also Patron of Erasmus Darwin House in Lichfield, the eighteenth-century home of Charles Darwin's grandfather, now a museum open to the public.
[src:ancient-history/adam-hart-davis] He has written many books, including a history of the toilet, entitled *Thunder, Flush and Thomas Crapper*, and *Taking The Piss* (*A Potted History of Pee*).
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The **Adena culture** was a pre-Columbian Native American culture that existed from 500 BC to 100 AD, in a time known as the Early Woodland period.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The Adena culture refers to what were probably a number of related Native American societies sharing a burial complex and ceremonial system.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The Adena culture was centered on the location of the modern state of Ohio, but also extended into contiguous areas of Kentucky, West Virginia, Indiana, Illinois, Southern Wisconsin and parts of extreme western Pennsylvania.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The Adena culture was named for the large mound on Thomas Worthington's early 19th-century estate located near Chillicothe, Ohio, which he named "Adena".
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The culture is the most prominently known of a number of similar cultures in eastern North America that began mound building ceremonialism at the end of the Archaic period.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The geographic range of the Adena sites is centered on central and southern Ohio, with further sites in contiguous areas of the surrounding states of Indiana, Kentucky, West Virginia and Pennsylvania.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The importance of the Adena complex comes from its considerable influence on other contemporary cultures and cultures that came after it.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The Adena culture is seen as the precursor to the traditions of the Hopewell tradition, which are sometimes thought as an elaboration, or zenith, of Adena traditions.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The Adena were notable for their agricultural practices, pottery, artistic works, and extensive trading network, which supplied them with a variety of raw materials, ranging from copper from the Great Lakes to shells from the Gulf Coast.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Lasting traces of Adena culture are still seen in the remains of their substantial earthworks.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] At one point, larger Adena mounds numbered in the hundreds, but only a small number of the remains of the larger Adena earthen monuments still survive today.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] These mounds generally ranged in size from 20 feet (6.1 m) to 300 feet (91 m) in diameter and served as burial structures, ceremonial sites, historical markers, and possibly gathering places.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] These earthen monuments were built using hundreds of thousands of baskets full of specially selected and graded earth.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] According to archaeological investigations, Adena earthworks were often built as part of their burial rituals, in which the earth of the earthwork was piled immediately atop a burned mortuary building.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] These mortuary buildings were intended to keep and maintain the dead until their final burial was performed.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Before the construction of the earthworks, some utilitarian and grave goods would be placed on the floor of the structure, which was burned with the goods and honored dead within.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The earthwork would then be constructed, and often a new mortuary structure would be placed atop the new earthwork.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] After a series of repetitions, mortuary/earthwork/mortuary/earthwork, a quite prominent earthwork would remain.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] In the later Adena period, circular ridges of unknown function were sometimes constructed around the burial earthworks.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The Great Serpent Mound in Ohio has been attributed to this culture, however, without conclusive evidence.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Their mounds are similar to mounds built in Sweden during the end of the Bronze age.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The Adena also carved small stone tablets, usually 4 or 5 inches by 3 or 4 inches by .5 inches thick.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] On one or both flat sides were gracefully composed stylized zoomorphs or curvilinear geometric designs in deep relief.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Paint has been found on some Adena tablets, leading archaeologists to propose that these stone tablets were probably used to stamp designs on cloth or animal hides, or onto their own bodies.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] It is possible that they were used to outline designs for tattooing.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Postholes from a number of timber circles have been found during excavations of Adena culture causewayed ring ditch sites in the Bluegrass region of Kentucky and adjacent regions of Ohio and West Virginia.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] A notable example was found by archaeologist William S.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Webb during the excavations of the Mount Horeb Site 1 in Fayette County, Kentucky in 1939.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Webb discovered a circle of "paired-posts" inside of the embankment ring and ditch.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The 48.5 feet (14.8 m) circle was made up of sixty two "paired" post sets and eight single posts.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Unlike in other cultures, Adena pottery was not buried with the dead or the remains of the cremated, as were other artifacts.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Usually Adena pottery was tempered with grit or crushed limestone and was very thick; its decoration was largely plain, cord-marked or fabric marked, although one type bore a nested-diamond design incised into its surface.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The vessel shapes were sub-conoidal or flat-bottomed jars, sometimes with small foot-like supports.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The large and elaborate mound sites served a nearby scattering of people.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The population was dispersed in small settlements of one to two structures.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] A typical house was built in a circle form from 15 to 45 feet in diameter.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The walls were made of paired posts tilted outward, that were then joined to other pieces of wood to form a cone shaped roof.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] The roof was then covered with bark and the walls may have been bark and/or wickerwork.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Their sustenance was acquired through foraging and the cultivation of native plants.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Somewhat rougher slab-like stones with chipped edges were probably used as hoes.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Bone and antler were used in small tools, but even more prominently in ornamental objects such as beads, combs, and worked animal-jaw gorgets or paraphernalia.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] Spoons, beads and other implements were made from the marine conch.
[src:ancient-history/adena-culture] A few copper axes have been found, but otherwise the metal was hammered into ornamental forms, such as bracelets, rings, beads, and reel-shaped pendants.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The **Aegean Sea** is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea between Europe and Asia.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] It is located between the Balkans and Anatolia, and covers an area of some 215,000 km2 (83,000 sq mi).
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In the north, the Aegean is connected to the Marmara Sea, which in turn connects to the Black Sea, by the straits of the Dardanelles and the Bosphorus, respectively.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are located within the sea and some bound it on its southern periphery, including Crete and Rhodes.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The sea reaches a maximum depth of 2,639 m (8,658 ft) to the west of Karpathos.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Thracian Sea and the Sea of Crete are main subdivisions of the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands can be divided into several island groups, including the Dodecanese, the Cyclades, the Sporades, the Saronic islands and the North Aegean Islands, as well as Crete and its surrounding islands.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Dodecanese, located to the southeast, includes the islands of Rhodes, Kos, and Patmos; the islands of Delos and Naxos are within the Cyclades to the south of the sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Lesbos is part of the North Aegean Islands.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Euboea, the second-largest island in Greece, is located in the Aegean, despite being administered as part of Central Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Nine out of twelve of the Administrative regions of Greece border the sea, along with the Turkish provinces of Edirne, Çanakkale, Balıkesir, İzmir, Aydın and Muğla to the east of the sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Various Turkish islands in the sea are Imbros, Tenedos, Cunda Island, and the Foça Islands.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea has been historically important, especially regarding the civilization of Ancient Greece, which inhabited the area around the coast of the Aegean and the Aegean islands.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands facilitated contact between the people of the area and between Europe and Asia.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Along with the Greeks, Thracians lived along the northern coasts.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Romans conquered the area under the Roman Empire, and later the Byzantine Empire held it against advances by the First Bulgarian Empire.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Fourth Crusade weakened Byzantine control of the area, and it was eventually conquered by the Ottoman Empire, with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onwards.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The rocks making up the floor of the Aegean are mainly limestone, though often greatly altered by volcanic activity that has convulsed the region in relatively recent geologic times.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Of particular interest are the richly colored sediments in the region of the islands of Santorini and Milos, in the south Aegean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Notable cities on the Aegean coastline include Athens, Thessaloniki, Heraklion, Volos, Alexandroupolis and Kavala in Greece, and İzmir and Bodrum in Turkey.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Several issues concerning sovereignty within the Aegean Sea are disputed between Greece and Turkey.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean dispute has had a large effect on Greece-Turkey relations since the 1970s.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Issues include the delimitation of territorial waters, national airspace, exclusive economic zones, and flight information regions.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Ancient Greek authors also called it the "Greek Sea".
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The sea was known in Latin as *Mare Aegaeum* while under the control of the Roman Empire.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Pliny the Elder write that the Romans used the terms "Macedonian" for the northern part near Macedonia and Thrace provinces, and "Grecian" for the part near Greece itself.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In medieval Latin, the Aegean Sea was known as *Egeopelagus*, a form attested as late as 1419 in Venetian state papers (Ducatus Egeopelagi) and derived from the Greek αἰγαιοπέλαγος / αἰγαῖον πέλαγος.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The term *Arcipelago* also appears, for instance in a treaty on 30 June 1268 between the Venetians and the emperor Michael Palaeologus.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] This term subsequently gave rise to *Archipelago* (Greek: αρχιπέλαγος), which in many European languages originally referred specifically to the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The terms *Greek Archipelago* or *Grecian Archipelago* were also used.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Later, as archipelago came to be used increasingly as a generic term for island-studded seas, the terms Greek Archipelago or Grecian Archipelago continued to be used alongside the ancient name, Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In some South Slavic languages, the Aegean is called *White Sea* (Bulgarian: Бяло море, romanized: *Byalo more*; Macedonian: Бело море, romanized: *Belo more*; Serbian: *Belo more* / Бело море).
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Turkish name for the sea is *Ege Denizi*, which is derived from the Greek name, and *Adalar Denizi* meaning "Sea of Islands".
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In the past, Turks also referred to it as the "White Sea", to differentiate it from the Black Sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea and covers about 214,000 square kilometres (83,000 sq mi) in area, measuring about 670 kilometres (420 mi) longitudinally and 390 kilometres (240 mi) latitudinal.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The sea's maximum depth is 2,639 metres (8,658 ft), located at a point west of Karpathos.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are found within its waters, with the following islands delimiting the sea on the south, generally from west to east: Kythera, Antikythera, Crete, Kasos, Karpathos and Rhodes.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Anatolian peninsula marks the eastern boundary of the sea, while the Greek mainland marks the west.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Several seas are contained within the Aegean Sea; the Thracian Sea is a section of the Aegean located to the north, the Icarian Sea to the east, the Myrtoan Sea to the west, while the Sea of Crete is the southern section.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Greek regions that border the sea, in alphabetical order, are Attica, Central Greece, Central Macedonia, Crete, Eastern Macedonia and Thrace, North Aegean, Peloponnese, South Aegean, and Thessaly.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The traditional Greek region of Macedonia also borders the sea, to the north.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Many of the Aegean islands or island chains, are geographical extensions of the mountains on the mainland.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] One chain extends across the sea to Chios, another extends across Euboea to Samos, and a third extends across the Peloponnese and Crete to Rhodes, dividing the Aegean from the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is connected to the Sea of Marmara by the Dardanelles, also known from Classical Antiquity as the Hellespont.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles are located to the northeast of the sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] It ultimately connects with the Black Sea through the Bosporus strait, upon which lies the city of Istanbul.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles and the Bosporus are known as the Turkish Straits.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Aegean surface water circulates in a counterclockwise gyre, with hypersaline Mediterranean water moving northward along the west coast of Turkey, before being displaced by less dense Black Sea outflow.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The dense Mediterranean water sinks below the Black Sea inflow to a depth of 23–30 metres (75–98 ft), then flows through the Dardanelles Strait and into the Sea of Marmara at velocities of 5–15 cm/s (2–6 in/s).
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Black Sea outflow moves westward along the northern Aegean Sea, then flows southwards along the east coast of Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The physical oceanography of the Aegean Sea is controlled mainly by the regional climate, the fresh water discharge from major rivers draining southeastern Europe, and the seasonal variations in the Black Sea surface water outflow through the Dardanelles Strait.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The climate of the Aegean Sea largely reflects the climate of Greece and Western Turkey, which is to say, predominantly Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] According to the Köppen climate classification, most of the Aegean is classified as Hot-summer Mediterranean (*Csa*), with hotter and drier summers along with milder and wetter winters.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] However, high temperatures during summers are generally not quite as high as those in arid or semiarid climates due to the presence of a large body of water.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] This is most predominant in the west and east coasts of the Aegean, and within the Aegean islands.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In the north of the Aegean Sea, the climate is instead classified as Cold semi-arid *(BSk)*, which feature cooler summers than Hot-summer Mediterranean climates.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Etesian winds are a dominant weather influence in the Aegean Basin.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Numerous Greek and Turkish settlements are located along their mainland coast, as well as on towns on the Aegean islands.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The largest cities are Athens and Thessaloniki in Greece and İzmir in Turkey.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The most populated of the Aegean islands is Crete, followed by Euboea and Rhodes.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Greece has established several marine protected areas along its coasts.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] According to the Network of Managers of Marine Protected Areas in the Mediterranean (MedPAN), four Greek MPAs are participating in the Network.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] These include Alonnisos Marine Park, while the Missolonghi–Aitoliko Lagoons and the island of Zakynthos are not on the Aegean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The current coastline dates back to about 4000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Before that time, at the peak of the last ice age (about 18,000 years ago) sea levels everywhere were 130 metres (430 ft) lower, and there were large well-watered coastal plains instead of much of the northern Aegean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] When they were first occupied, the present-day islands including Milos with its important obsidian production were probably still connected to the mainland.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The present coastal arrangement appeared around 9,000 years ago, with post-ice age sea levels continuing to rise for another 3,000 years after that.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The subsequent Bronze Age civilizations of Greece and the Aegean Sea have given rise to the general term *Aegean civilization*.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In ancient times, the sea was the birthplace of two ancient civilizations – the Minoans of Crete and the Mycenaeans of the Peloponnese.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Minoan civilization was a Bronze Age civilization on the island of Crete and other Aegean islands, flourishing from around 3000 to 1450 BC before a period of decline, finally ending at around 1100 BC.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] It represented the first advanced civilization in Europe, leaving behind massive building complexes, tools, stunning artwork, writing systems, and a massive network of trade.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Minoan period saw extensive trade between Crete, Aegean, and Mediterranean settlements, particularly the Near East.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The most notable Minoan palace is that of Knossos, followed by that of Phaistos.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Mycenaean Greeks arose on the mainland, becoming the first advanced civilization in mainland Greece, which lasted from approximately 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] It is believed that the site of Mycenae, which sits close to the Aegean coast, was the center of Mycenaean civilization.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Mycenaeans introduced several innovations in the fields of engineering, architecture and military infrastructure, while trade over vast areas of the Mediterranean, including the Aegean, was essential for the Mycenaean economy.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Their syllabic script, the Linear B, offers the first written records of the Greek language and their religion already included several deities that can also be found in the Olympic Pantheon.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Mycenaean Greece was dominated by a warrior elite society and consisted of a network of palace-centered states that developed rigid hierarchical, political, social and economic systems.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] At the head of this society was the king, known as *wanax*.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The civilization of Mycenaean Greeks perished with the collapse of Bronze Age culture in the eastern Mediterranean, to be followed by the so-called Greek Dark Ages.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] It is undetermined what cause the collapse of the Mycenaeans.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] During the Greek Dark Ages, writing in the Linear B script ceased, vital trade links were lost, and towns and villages were abandoned.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Archaic period followed the Greek Dark Ages in the 8th century BC.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Greece became divided into small self-governing communities, and adopted the Phoenician alphabet, modifying it to create the Greek alphabet.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] By the 6th century BC several cities had emerged as dominant in Greek affairs: Athens, Sparta, Corinth, and Thebes, of which Athens, Sparta, and Corinth were closest to the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Each of them had brought the surrounding rural areas and smaller towns under their control, and Athens and Corinth had become major maritime and mercantile powers as well.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In the 8th and 7th centuries BC many Greeks migrated to form colonies in Magna Graecia (Southern Italy and Sicily), Asia Minor and further afield.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea was the setting for one of the most pivotal naval engagements in history, when, on 20 September 480 B.C., the Athenian fleet gained a decisive victory over the Persian fleet of the Xerxes II of Persia at the Battle of Salamis.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Thus ending any further attempt of western expansion by the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea would later come to be under the control, albeit briefly, of the Kingdom of Macedonia.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Philip II and his son Alexander the Great led a series of conquests that led not only to the unification of the Greek mainland and the control of the Aegean Sea under his rule, but also the destruction of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] After Alexander the Great's death, his empire was divided among his generals.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Cassander became king of the Hellenistic kingdom of Macedon, which held territory along the western coast of the Aegean, roughly corresponding to modern-day Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Kingdom of Lysimachus had control over the sea's eastern coast.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Greece had entered the Hellenistic period.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Macedonian Wars were a series of conflicts fought by the Roman Republic and its Greek allies in the eastern Mediterranean against several different major Greek kingdoms.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] They resulted in Roman control or influence over the eastern Mediterranean basin, including the Aegean, in addition to their hegemony in the western Mediterranean after the Punic Wars.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] During Roman rule, the land around the Aegean Sea fell under the provinces of Achaea, Macedonia, Thracia, Asia and Creta et Cyrenaica (island of Crete).
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The fall of the Western Roman Empire allowed its successor state, the Byzantine Empire, to continue Roman control over the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] However, their territory would later be threatened by the early Muslim conquests initiated by Muhammad in the 7th century.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Although the Rashidun Caliphate did not manage to obtain land along the coast of the Aegean Sea, its conquest of the Eastern Anatolian peninsula as well as Egypt, the Levant, and North Africa left the Byzantine Empire weakened.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Umayyad Caliphate expanded the territorial gains of the Rashidun Caliphate, conquering much of North Africa, and threatened the Byzantine Empire's control of Western Anatolia, where it meets the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] During the 820s, Crete was conquered by a group of Berbers Andalusians exiles led by Abu Hafs Umar al-Iqritishi, and it became an independent Islamic state.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Byzantine Empire launched a campaign that took most of the island back in 842 and 843 under Theoktistos, but the re-conquest was not completed and was soon reversed.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Later attempts by the Byzantine Empire to recover the island were without success.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] For the approximately 135 years of its existence, the emirate of Crete was one of the major foes of Byzantium.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Crete commanded the sea lanes of the Eastern Mediterranean and functioned as a forward base and haven for Muslim corsair fleets that ravaged the Byzantine-controlled shores of the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Crete returned to Byzantine rule under Nikephoros II Phokas, who launched a huge campaign against the Emirate of Crete in 960 to 961.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Meanwhile, the Bulgarian Empire threatened Byzantine control of Northern Greece and the Aegean coast to the south.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Under Presian and his successor Boris I, the Bulgarian Empire managed to obtain a small portion of the northern Aegean coast.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Simeon I of Bulgaria led Bulgaria to its greatest territorial expansion, and managed to conqueror much of the northern and western coasts of the Aegean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Second Bulgarian Empire achieved similar success along, again, the northern and western coasts, under Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Seljuk Turks, under the Seljuk Empire, invaded the Byzantine Empire in 1068, from which they annexed almost all the territories of Anatolia, including the east coast of the Aegean Sea, during the reign of Alp Arslan, the second Sultan of the Seljuk Empire.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] After the death of his successor, Malik Shah I, the empire was divided, and Malik Shah was succeeded in Anatolia by Kilij Arslan I, who founded the Sultanate of Rum.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Byzantines yet again recaptured the eastern coast of the Aegean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Venetians created the maritime state of the Duchy of the Archipelago, which included all the Cyclades except Mykonos and Tinos.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Empire of Nicaea, a Byzantine rump state, managed to affect the Recapture of Constantinople from the Latins in 1261 and defeat Epirus.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Byzantine successes were not to last; the Ottomans would conquer the area around the Aegean coast, but before their expansion the Byzantine Empire had already been weakened from internal conflict.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] By the late 14th century, the Byzantine Empire had lost all control of the coast of the Aegean Sea and could only exercise power around their capital, Constantinople.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire then gained control of all the Aegean coast with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onward.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In the aftermath of the Balkan Wars (1912–1913) Greece expanded northwards along the coast, while Bulgaria gained access in the northernmost section of the sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until its dissolution following World War I, when it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] After the war, Greece gained control over the area around the northern coast of the Aegean, including the territory held by Bulgaria.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] By the 1920s, Greece and Turkey had about resumed their present-day borders.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In the Italo-Turkish War of 1912, Italy captured the Dodecanese islands, and had occupied them since, reneging on the 1919 Venizelos–Tittoni agreement to cede them to Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Greco-Italian War took place from October 1940 to April 1941 as part of the Balkans Campaign of World War II.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Italian war aim was to establish a Greek puppet state, which would permit the Italian annexation of the Sporades and Cyclades islands in the Aegean Sea, to be administered as a part of the Italian Aegean Islands.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The German invasion resulted in the Axis occupation of Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The German troops evacuated Athens on 12 October 1944, and by the end of the month, they had withdrawn from mainland Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Greece was then liberated by Allied troops.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Many of the islands in the Aegean have safe harbours and bays.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In ancient times, navigation through the sea was easier than travelling across the rough terrain of the Greek mainland, and to some extent, the coastal areas of Anatolia.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Many of the islands are volcanic, and marble and iron are mined on other islands.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The larger islands have some fertile valleys and plains.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Of the main islands in the Aegean Sea, two belong to Turkey – Bozcaada (Tenedos) and Gökçeada (Imbros); the rest belong to Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Between the two countries, there are political disputes over several aspects of political control over the Aegean space, including the size of territorial waters, air control and the delimitation of economic rights to the continental shelf.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] These issues are known as the Aegean dispute.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Multiple ports are located along the Greek and Turkish coasts of the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The port of Piraeus in Athens is the chief port in Greece, the largest passenger port in Europe and the third largest in the world, servicing about 20 million passengers annually.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] With a throughput of 1.4 million TEUs, Piraeus is placed among the top ten ports in container traffic in Europe and the top container port in the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Piraeus is also the commercial hub of Greek shipping.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Piraeus bi-annually acts as the focus for a major shipping convention, known as Posidonia, which attracts maritime industry professionals from all over the world.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Piraeus is currently Greece's third-busiest port in terms of tons of goods transported, behind Agioi Theodoroi and Thessaloniki.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The central port serves ferry routes to almost every island in the eastern portion of Greece, the island of Crete, the Cyclades, the Dodecanese, and much of the northern and the eastern Aegean Sea, while the western part of the port is used for cargo services.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] As of 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki was the second-largest container port in Greece after the port of Piraeus, making it one of the busiest ports in Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] In 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki handled 14,373,245 tonnes of cargo and 222,824 TEU's.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Paloukia, on the island of Salamis, is a major passenger port.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Fish are Greece's second-largest agricultural export, and Greece has Europe's largest fishing fleet.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Fish captured include sardines, mackerel, grouper, grey mullets, sea bass, and seabream.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] There is a considerable difference between fish catches between the pelagic and demersal zones; with respect to pelagic fisheries, the catches from the northern, central and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated, respectively, by anchovy, horse mackerels, and boops.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] For demersal fisheries, the catches from the northern and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated by grey mullets and pickerel (*Spicara smaris*) respectively.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The industry has been impacted by the Great Recession.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Overfishing and habitat destruction is also a concern, threatening grouper, and seabream populations, resulting in perhaps a 50% decline of fish catch.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] To address these concerns, Greek fishermen have been offered a compensation by the government.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Although some species are defined as protected or threatened under EU legislation, several illegal species such as the molluscs *Pinna nobilis*, *Charonia tritonis* and *Lithophaga lithophaga*, can be bought in restaurants and fish markets around Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands within the Aegean Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Tourism to the Aegean islands contributes a significant portion of tourism in Greece, especially since the second half of the 20th century.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] A total of five UNESCO World Heritage sites are located the Aegean Islands; these include the Monastery of Saint John the Theologian and the Cave of the Apocalypse on Patmos, the Pythagoreion and Heraion of Samos in Samos, the Nea Moni of Chios, the island of Delos, and the Medieval City of Rhodes.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Greece is one of the most visited countries in Europe and the world with over 33 million visitors in 2018, and the tourism industry around a quarter of Greece's Gross Domestic Product.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The islands of Santorini, Crete, Lesbos, Delos, and Mykonos are common tourist destinations.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] An estimated 2 million tourists visit Santorini annually.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] However, concerns relating to overtourism have arisen in recent years, such as issues of inadequate infrastructure and overcrowding.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Alongside Greece, Turkey has also been successful in developing resort areas and attracting large number of tourists, contributing to tourism in Turkey.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The phrase "Blue Cruise" refers to recreational voyages along the Turkish Riviera, including across the Aegean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The ancient city of Troy, a World Heritage Site, is on the Turkish coast of the Aegean.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Greece and Turkey both take part in the Blue Flag beach certification programme of the Foundation for Environmental Education.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] The certification is awarded for beaches and marinas meeting strict quality standards including environmental protection, water quality, safety and services criteria.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] As of 2015, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 395 beaches and 9 marinas in Greece.
[src:ancient-history/aegean-sea] Southern Aegean beaches on the Turkish coast include Muğla, with 102 beaches awarded with the blue flag, along with İzmir and Aydın, who have 49 and 30 beaches awarded respectively.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Well-known ancient artwork and sculptures, each representing a certain civilisation.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] The three-age system periodises ancient history into the Stone Age, the Bronze Age, and the Iron Age, with recorded history usually considered to begin with the Bronze Age.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] The start and end of the three ages vary between world regions.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] In many regions the Bronze Age is generally considered to begin a few centuries prior to 3000 BC, while the end of the Iron Age varies from the early first millennium BC in some regions to the late first millennium AD in others.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] During the time period of ancient history, the world population was exponentially increasing due to the Neolithic Revolution, which was in full progress.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] In 10,000 BC, the world population stood at an estimated 2 million, it rose to 45 million by 3000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] By the Iron Age in 1000 BC, the population had risen to 72 million.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] By the end of the ancient period in AD 500, the world population is thought to have stood at 209 million.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] In 10,500 years, the world population increased by 100 times.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Prehistory is the period before written history.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Most of the knowledge of that period comes from the work of archaeologists.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] The early human migrations in the Lower Paleolithic saw *Homo erectus* spread across Eurasia 1.8 million years ago.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Evidence for the use of fire has been dated as early as 1.8 million years ago, a date which is contested, with generally accepted evidence for the controlled use of fire dating to 780,000 years ago.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Actual use of hearths first appears 400,000 years ago.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Dates for the emergence of *Homo sapiens* (modern humans) range from 250,000 to 160,000 years ago, with the varying dates being based on DNA studies and fossils respectively.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Some 50,000 years ago, *Homo sapiens* migrated out of Africa.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] They reached Australia about 45,000 years ago, southwestern Europe about the same time, southeastern Europe and Siberia around 40,000 years ago, and Japan about 30,000 years ago.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Humans migrated to the Americas about 15,000 years ago.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Evidence for agriculture emerges in about 9000 BC in what is now eastern Turkey and spread through the Fertile Crescent.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Settlement at Göbekli Tepe began around 9500 BC and may have the world's oldest temple.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] The Nile River Valley has evidence of sorghum and millet cultivation starting around 8000 BC and agricultural use of yams in Western Africa perhaps dates to the same time period.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Cultivation of millet, rice, and legumes began around 7000 BC in China.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Taro cultivation in New Guinea dates to about 7000 BC also with squash cultivation in Mesoamerica perhaps sharing that date.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Animal domestication began with the domestication of dogs, which dates to at least 15,000 years ago, and perhaps even earlier.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Sheep and goats were domesticated around 9000 BC in the Fertile Crescent, alongside the first evidence for agriculture.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Other animals, such as pigs and poultry, were later domesticated and used as food sources.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Cattle and water buffalo were domesticated around 7000 BC and horses, donkeys, and camels were domesticated by about 4000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] All of these animals were used not only for food, but to carry and pull people and loads, greatly increasing human ability to do work.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] The invention of the simple plough by 6000 BC further increased agricultural efficiency.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Metal use in the form of hammered copper items predates the discovery of smelting of copper ores, which happened around 6000 BC in western Asia and independently in eastern Asia before 2000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Gold and silver use dates to between 6000 and 5000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Alloy metallurgy began with bronze in about 3500 BC in Mesopotamia and was developed independently in China by 2000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Pottery developed independently throughout the world, with fired pots appearing first among the Jomon of Japan and in West Africa at Mali.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Sometime between 5000 and 4000 BC the potter's wheel was invented.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] By 3000 BC, the pottery wheel was adapted into wheeled vehicles which could be used to carry loads further and easier than with human or animal power alone.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Writing developed separately in five different locations in human history: Mesopotamia, Egypt, India, China, and Mesoamerica.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] By 3400 BC, "proto-literate" cuneiform spread in the Middle East.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Egypt developed its own system of hieroglyphs by about 3200 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] By 2800 BC the Indus Valley Civilisation had developed its Indus script, which remains undeciphered.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Chinese Characters were independently developed in China during the Shang dynasty in the form of the Oracle Bone Script dating to the period 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p01] Writing in Mesoamerica dates to 600 BC with the Zapotec civilization.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The ancient Near East is considered the cradle of civilisation.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It began the study of the stars and the sciences of astronomy and mathematics.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Mesopotamia is the site of some of the earliest known civilisations in the world.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Agricultural communities emerged in the area with the Halaf culture around 8000 BC and continued to expand through the Ubaid period around 6000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Cities began in the Uruk period (4000–3100 BC) and expanded during the Jemdet Nasr (3100–2900 BC) and Early Dynastic (2900–2350 BC) periods.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The surplus of storable foodstuffs created by this economy allowed the population to settle in one place instead of migrating after crops and herds.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It also allowed for a much greater population density, and in turn required an extensive labour force and division of labour.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This organisation led to the necessity of record keeping and the development of writing.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Babylonia was an Amorite state in lower Mesopotamia (modern southern Iraq), with Babylon as its capital.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Babylonia emerged when Hammurabi created an empire out of the territories of the former kingdoms of Sumer and Akkad.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire, or Chaldea, was Babylonia from the 7th and 6th centuries BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Under the reign of Nebuchadnezzar II, it conquered Jerusalem.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This empire also created the Hanging Gardens of Babylon and the still-surviving Ishtar Gate as architectural embellishments of its capital at Babylon.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Akkad was a city and its surrounding region near Babylon.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Akkad also became the capital of the Akkadian Empire.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Despite an extensive search, the precise site has never been found.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Akkad reached the height of its power between about 2330 and 2150 BC, following the conquests of King Sargon of Akkad.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Through the spread of Sargon's empire, the language of Akkad, known as Akkadian from the city, spread and replaced the Sumerian language in Mesopotamia and eventually by 1450 BC was the main language of diplomacy in the Near East.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Assyria was originally a region on the Upper Tigris, where a small state was created in the 19th century BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The capital was at Assur, which gave the state its name.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Later, as a nation and empire that came to control all of the Fertile Crescent, Egypt, and much of Anatolia, the term "Assyria proper" referred to roughly the northern half of Mesopotamia (the southern half being Babylonia), with Nineveh as its capital.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Assyrian kings controlled a large kingdom at three different times in history.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] These are called the *Old* (20th to 18th centuries BC), *Middle* (14th to 11th centuries BC), and *Neo-Assyrian* (9th to 7th centuries BC) kingdoms, or periods.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Mitanni was a Hurrian empire in northern Mesopotamia founded around 1500 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Mitanians conquered and controlled Assyria until the 14th century BC while contending with Egypt for control of parts of modern Syria.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Its capital was Washukanni, whose precise location has not been determined by archaeologists.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Medes and Persians were peoples who had appeared in the Iranian plateau around 1500 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Both peoples spoke Indo-European languages and were mostly pastoralists with a tradition of horse archery.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Medes established their own Median Empire by the 6th century BC, having defeated the Neo-Assyrian Empire with the Chaldeans in 614 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Achaemenid Empire was founded by Cyrus the Great, who first became king of the Persians, then conquered the Medes, Lydia, and Babylon by 539 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The empire built on earlier Mesopotamian systems of government to govern their large empire.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] By building roads, they improved both the ability to send governmental instructions throughout their lands as well as improving the ability of their military forces to be deployed rapidly.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Increased trade and upgraded farming techniques increased wealth, but also exacerbated inequalities between social classes.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The empire's location at the centre of trading networks spread its intellectual and philosophical ideas throughout a wide area, and its religion, while not itself spreading far, had an impact on later religions such as Christianity, Islam, and Judaism.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Cyrus' son Cambyses II conquered Egypt, while a later emperor, Darius the Great, expanded the empire to the Indus River, creating the largest empire in the world to that date.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] But Darius and his son Xerxes I failed to expand into Greece, with expeditions in 490 and 480 BC eventually failing.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Achaemenid dynasty and empire fell to Alexander the Great by 330 BC, and after Alexander's death, much of the area previously ruled by the Cyrus and his successors was ruled by the Seleucid dynasty.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Parthia was an Iranian civilisation situated in the northeastern part of modern Iran.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Their power was based on a combination of military power based on heavy cavalry with a decentralised governing structure based on a federated system.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Parthian Empire was led by the Arsacid dynasty, which by around 155 BC under Mithradates I had mostly conquered the Seleucid Empire.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Parthia had many wars with the Romans, but it was rebellions within the empire that ended it in the 3rd century AD.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Sasanian Empire began when the Parthian Empire ended in AD 224.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Their rulers claimed the Achaemenids as ancestors and set up their capital at Ctesiphon in Mesopotamia.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Their period of greatest military expansion occurred under Shapur I, who by the time of his death in AD 272 had defeated Roman imperial armies and set up buffer states between the Sasanians and Roman Empires.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] After Shapur, the Sasanians were under more pressure from the Kushans to their east as well as the Roman then Byzantine Empire to its west.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] However, the Sasanians rebuilt and founded numerous cities and their merchants travelled widely and introduced crops such as sugar, rice, and cotton into the Iranian plateau.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] But in AD 651, the last Sassanid emperor was killed by the expanding Islamic Arabs.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Hittites first came to Anatolia about 1900 BC and during the period 1600–1500 they expanded into Mesopotamia where they adopted the cuneiform script to their Indo-European language.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] By 1200 their empire stretched to Phoenicia and eastern Anatolia.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] They improved two earlier technologies from Mesopotamia and spread these new techniques widely – improved iron working and light chariots with spoked wheels in warfare.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Hittites introduced the casting of iron with molds and then hammering it which enabled weapons and tools to be made stronger and also cheaper.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Although chariots had been used previously, the use of spoked wheels allowed the chariots to be much lighter and more maneuverable.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] In 1274 BC the Hittites clashed with the Egyptians at the Battle of Kadesh, where both sides claimed victory.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] In 1207 BC the Hittite capital of Hattusa was sacked, ending the Hittite Empire.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Israel and Judah were related Iron Age kingdoms of the ancient Levant and had existed during the Iron Ages and the Neo-Babylonian, Persian and Hellenistic periods.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The name Israel first appears in the stele of the Egyptian pharaoh Merneptah around 1209 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This "Israel" was a cultural and probably political entity of the central highlands, well enough established to be perceived by the Egyptians as a possible challenge to their hegemony, but an ethnic group rather than an organised state.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Israel had emerged by the middle of the 9th century BC, when the Assyrian King Shalmaneser III named "Ahab the Israelite" among his enemies at the battle of Qarqar (853).
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Judah emerged somewhat later than Israel, probably during the 9th century BC, but the subject is one of considerable controversy.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Israel came into conflict with the Assyrians, who conquered Israel in 722 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire did the same to Judah in 586.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] After both conquests, the conquering forces deported many of the inhabitants to other regions of their respective empires.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Phoenicia was an ancient civilisation centred in the north of ancient Canaan, with its heartland along the coastal regions of modern-day Lebanon, Syria and Israel.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Phoenician civilisation was an enterprising maritime trading culture that spread across the Mediterranean between the period of 1550 to 300 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] One Phoenician colony, Carthage, ruled an empire in the Western Mediterranean until being defeated by Rome in the Punic Wars.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Phoenicians invented the Phoenician alphabet, the forerunner of the modern alphabet still in use today.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The history of Pre-Islamic Arabia before the rise of Islam in the AD 630s is not known in great detail.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Archaeological exploration in the Arabian Peninsula has been sparse; indigenous written sources are limited to the many inscriptions and coins from southern Arabia.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Existing material consists primarily of written sources from other traditions (such as Egyptians, Greeks, Persians, Romans, etc.) and oral traditions later recorded by Islamic scholars.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] A number of small kingdoms existed in Arabia from around AD 100 to perhaps about AD 400.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egypt was a long-lived civilisation geographically located in north-eastern Africa.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It was concentrated along the middle to lower reaches of the Nile River, reaching its greatest extent during the 2nd millennium BC, which is referred to as the New Kingdom period.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It reached broadly from the Nile Delta in the north, as far south as Jebel Barkal at the Fourth Cataract of the Nile.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Extensions to the geographical range of ancient Egyptian civilisation included, at different times, areas of the southern Levant, the Eastern Desert and the Red Sea coastline, the Sinai Peninsula, and the Western Desert (focused on the several oases).
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egypt developed over at least three and a half millennia.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It began with the incipient unification of Nile Valley polities around 3100 BC, traditionally under Menes.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Overseeing these activities were a socio-political and economic elite under the figure of a (semi)-divine ruler from a succession of ruling dynasties.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egyptian history is divided across various periods, beginning with the Old Kingdom, which saw pyramid building on a large scale.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] After 2100 BC, the Old Kingdom dissolved into smaller states during the First Intermediate Period, which lasted about 100 years.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Middle Kingdom began around 2000 BC with the reunification of Egypt under pharoes ruling from Thebes.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Middle Kingdom ended with the conquest of northern Egypt by the Hyksos around 1650 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Hyksos were expelled from Egypt and the land was reunited in the New Kingdom around 1550 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This period lasted until about 1000 BC, and saw Egypt expand its borders into Palestine and Syria.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Third Intermediate Period was marked by the rule of priests as well as the conquest of Egypt by Nubian kings and then later Assyria, Persia, and Macedonians.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Carthage was founded around 814 BC by Phoenician settlers.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Carthage was a city-state that ruled an empire through alliances and trade influence that stretched throughout North Africa and modern Spain.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] At the height of the city's influence, its empire included most of the western Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The empire was in a constant state of struggle with the Roman Republic, which led to a series of conflicts known as the Punic Wars.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] After the third and final Punic War, Carthage was destroyed and then occupied by Roman forces.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Nearly all of the territory held by Carthage fell into Roman hands.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Ta-Seti kingdom in Nubia to the south of Egypt was conquered by Egyptian rulers around 3100 BC, but by 2500 BC the Nubians had created a new kingdom further south, known as the Kingdom of Kush, centred on the upper Nile with a capital at Kerma.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] In the Egyptian New Kingdom period, Kush once more was conquered by Egypt.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] However, by 1100 BC a new kingdom of Kush had formed, with a capital at Napata.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Nubian rulers conquered Egypt around 760 BC and retained control for about a century.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum was an important trading nation in northeastern Africa centred in present-day Eritrea and northern Ethiopia, it existed from approximately AD 100 to 940, growing from the Iron Age proto-Aksumite period around the 4th century BC to achieve prominence by the 1st century AD.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum at its height by the early 6th-century AD extended through much of modern Ethiopia and across the Red Sea to Arabia.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The capital city of the empire was Aksum, now in northern Ethiopia.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Nok culture appeared in Nigeria around 1000 BC and mysteriously vanished around AD 200.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The civilisation's social system is thought to have been highly advanced.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Nok civilisation was considered to be the earliest sub-Saharan producer of life-sized Terracotta which have been discovered by archaeologists.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Nok also used iron smelting that may have been independently developed.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The civilisation of Djenné-Djenno was located in the Niger River Valley in the country of Mali and is considered to be among the oldest urbanised centres and the best-known archaeology site in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This archaeological site is located about 3 kilometers (1.9 miles) away from the modern town and is believed to have been involved in long-distance trade and possibly the domestication of African rice.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The site is believed to exceed 33 hectares (82 acres); however, this is yet to be confirmed with extensive survey work.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] With the help of archaeological excavations mainly by Susan and Roderick McIntosh, the site is known to have been occupied from 250 BC to AD 900.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The city is believed to have been abandoned and moved where the current city is located due to the spread of Islam and the building of the Great Mosque of Djenné.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Previously, it was assumed that advanced trade networks and complex societies did not exist in the region until the arrival of traders from Southwest Asia.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] However, sites such as Djenné-Djenno disprove this, as these traditions in West Africa flourished long before.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Towns similar to that at Djenne-Jeno also developed at the site of Dia, also in Mali along the Niger River, from around 900 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Dhar Tichitt and Oualata were prominent among the early urban centres, dated to 2000 BC, in present-day Mauritania.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] About 500 stone settlements littered the region in the former savannah of the Sahara.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It has been found that the Soninke of the Mandé peoples were responsible for constructing such settlements.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Around 300 BC, the region became more desiccated and the settlements began to decline, most likely relocating to Koumbi Saleh.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] From the type of architecture and pottery, it is believed that Tichit was related to the subsequent Ghana Empire.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Old Jenne (Djenne) began to be settled around 300 BC, producing iron and with sizeable population, evidenced in crowded cemeteries.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The inhabitants and creators of these settlements during these periods are thought to have been ancestors of the Soninke people.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Peoples speaking precursors to the modern-day Bantu languages began to spread throughout southern Africa, and by 2000 BC they were expanding past the Congo River and into the Great Lakes area.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] By AD 1000 these groups had spread throughout all of southern Africa south of the equator.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Iron metallurgy and agriculture spread along with these peoples, with the cultivation of millet, oil palms, sorghum, and yams as well as the use of domesticated cattle, pigs, and sheep.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] These technologies helped increase population, and settled communities became common in sub-Saharan Africa except in deserts or heavy forests.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Paleolithic tools have been discovered in India dating to 200,000 years ago, and Neolithic sites are known from near the Indus Valley dating to around 8000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Agriculture began in the Indus Valley around 7000 BC, and reached the Ganges Valley by 3000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Barley, cotton, and wheat were grown and the population had domesticated cattle, goats, and sheep.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Indus Valley Civilisation developed around 3000 BC in the Indus and Ghaggar-Hakra river valleys of north-east Afghanistan, Pakistan, and western India.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Another name for this civilisation is Harappan, after the first of its cities to be excavated, Harappa (now in the Pakistani province of Punjab).
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Harappan civilisation grew out of the earlier agricultural communities as they evolved into cities.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] These communities created and traded jewelry, figurines, and seals that appear widely scattered throughout Mesopotamia, Afghanistan, and Iran.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Chickens were domesticated in addition to the earlier crops and animals.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] They developed their own writing system, the Indus Valley script, which is still mostly undeciphered.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The exact structure of society and the way the cities were governed is not known.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] By about 1600 BC, the Indus Valley culture had abandoned many of their cities, including Mohenjo-Daro.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The exact reason for this decline is not known.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Indo-European speaking peoples began to spread into India about 1500 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The *Rigveda*, in Sanskrit, dates to this period and begins a period often known as the Vedic period.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Between 1500 and 500 BC these peoples spread throughout most of India and had begun to found small cities.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Vedic society was characterised by the *varna* system which divided society into four broad castes, which were later elaborated.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] By the end of the Vedic period, this way of organising society had become central to Indian society.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Religion in the late Vedic period was evolving into Hinduism, which spread throughout Southeast Asia.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Siddhartha Gautama, born around 560 BC in northern India, went on to found a new religion based on his ascetic life – Buddhism.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This faith also spread throughout Eastern and Southeastern Asia after his death.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This period also saw the composition of the epics *Ramayana* and *Mahabharata*.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The kingdom of Magadha rose to prominence under a number of dynasties that peaked in power under the reign of Ashoka Maurya, one of India's most legendary and famous emperors.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] During the reign of Ashoka, the four dynasties of Chola, Chera, and Pandya were ruling in the South, while Devanampiya Tissa (250–210 BC) controlled Anuradhapura (now Sri Lanka).
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] These kingdoms, while not part of Ashoka's empire, were in friendly terms with the Maurya Empire.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] An alliance existed between Devanampiya Tissa and Ashoka of India, who sent Buddhist missionaries to Sri Lanka.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Most of North India was reunited under the Gupta Empire beginning under Chandragupta I around AD 320.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Under his successors the empire spread to include much of India except for the Deccan Plateau and the very south of the peninsula.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This was a period of relative peace, and the Gupta rulers generally left administration in local rulers.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Gupta Empire was weakened and ultimately ruined by the raids of Hunas (a branch of the Hephthalites emanating from Central Asia), and the empire broke up into smaller regional kingdoms by the end of the fifth century AD.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] India would remain fragmented into smaller states until the rise of the Mughal Empire in the 1500s.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Neolithic period of Southeast Asia was characterised by several migrations into Mainland and Island Southeast Asia from southern China by Austronesian, Austroasiatic, Kra-Dai, and Hmong–Mien speakers.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Territorial principalities in both Insular and Mainland Southeast Asia, characterised as "agrarian kingdoms", developed an economy by around 500 BC based on surplus crop cultivation and moderate coastal trade of domestic natural products.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Several states of the Malayan-Indonesian "thalassian" zone shared these characteristics with Indochinese polities like the Pyu city-states in the Irrawaddy River valley, the Văn Lang kingdom in the Red River Delta and Funan around the lower Mekong.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Văn Lang, founded in the 7th century BC, endured until 258 BC under the Hồng Bàng dynasty, as part of the Đông Sơn culture that sustained a dense and organised population that produced an elaborate Bronze Age industry.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Intensive wet-rice cultivation in an ideal climate enabled the farming communities to produce a regular crop surplus that was used by the ruling elite to raise, command and pay work forces for public construction and maintenance projects such as canals and fortifications.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The earliest known evidence of copper and bronze production in Southeast Asia was found at Ban Chiang in north-east Thailand and among the Phùng Nguyên culture of northern Vietnam around 2000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Đông Sơn culture established a tradition of bronze production and the manufacture of evermore refined bronze and iron objects, such as plows, axes and sickles with shaft holes, socketed arrows and spearheads and small ornamented items.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] By about 500 BC, large and delicately decorated bronze drums of remarkable quality, weighing more than 70 kg (150 lb), were produced in the laborious lost-wax casting process.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This industry of highly sophisticated metal processing was developed independent of Chinese or Indian influence.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Historians relate these achievements to the presence of organised, centralised and hierarchical communities and a large population.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Between 1000 BC and 100 AD, the Sa Huỳnh culture flourished along the south-central coast of Vietnam.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Ceramic jar burial sites that included grave goods have been discovered at various sites along the entire territory.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Among large, thin-walled terracotta jars, ornamented and colorized cooking pots, glass items, jade earrings and metal objects were deposited near the rivers and along the coast.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Around 3000 to 1500 BC, a large-scale migration of Austronesians, known as the Austronesian expansion began from Taiwan.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Population growth primarily fuelled this migration.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] These first settlers settled in northern Luzon, in the archipelago of the Philippines, intermingling with the earlier Australo-Melanesian population who had inhabited the islands since about 23,000 years earlier.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Over the next thousand years, Austronesian peoples migrated southeast to the rest of the Philippines, and into the islands of the Celebes Sea and Borneo.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] From southwestern Borneo, Austronesians spread further west in a single migration event to both Sumatra and the coastal regions of southern Vietnam, becoming the ancestors of the speakers of the Malayic and Chamic branches of the Austronesian language family.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Soon after reaching the Philippines, Austronesians colonised the Northern Mariana Islands by 1500 BC or even earlier, becoming the first humans to reach Remote Oceania.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Chamorro migration was also unique in that it was the only Austronesian migration to the Pacific Islands to successfully retain rice cultivation.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Palau and Yap were settled by separate voyages by 1000 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Another important migration branch was by the Lapita culture, which rapidly spread into the islands off the coast of northern New Guinea and into the Solomon Islands and other parts of coastal New Guinea and Island Melanesia by 1200 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] They reached the islands of Fiji, Samoa, and Tonga by around 900 to 800 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] This remained the furthest extent of the Austronesian expansion into Polynesia until around 700 AD, when there was another surge of island colonisation.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It reached the Cook Islands, Tahiti, and the Marquesas by 700 AD; Hawaii by 900 AD; Rapa Nui by 1000 AD; and New Zealand by 1200 AD.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] For a few centuries, the Polynesian islands were connected by bidirectional long-distance sailing, with the exception of Rapa Nui, which had limited further contact due to its isolated geographical location.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Island groups like the Pitcairns, the Kermadec Islands, and the Norfolk Islands were also formerly settled by Austronesians but later abandoned.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] There is also putative evidence, based in the spread of the sweet potato, that Austronesians may have reached South America from Polynesia, where they might have traded with the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Austronesians established prehistoric maritime trade networks in Island Southeast Asia, including the Maritime Jade Road, a jade trade network, in Southeast Asia which existed in Taiwan and the Philippines from 2000 BC to 1000 AD.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The trade was established by links between the indigenous peoples of Taiwan and the Philippines, and later included parts of Vietnam, Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, and other areas in Southeast Asia (known as the Sa Huynh-Kalanay Interaction Sphere).
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Lingling-o artefacts are among the notable archaeological finds originating from the Maritime Jade Road.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] During the operation of the Maritime Jade Road, the Austronesian spice trade networks were also established by Islander Southeast Asians with Sri Lanka and Southern India by around 1000 to 600 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] They also established early long-distance contacts with Africa, possibly as early as before 500 BC, based on such archaeological evidence as banana phytoliths in Cameroon and Uganda and remains of Neolithic chicken bones in Zanzibar.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] An Austronesian group, originally from the Makassar Strait region around Kalimantan and Sulawesi, eventually settled Madagascar, either directly from Southeast Asia or from preexisting mixed Austronesian-Bantu populations from East Africa.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Estimates for when this occurred vary from the 1st century AD to as late as the 6th to 7th centuries AD.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It is likely that the Austronesians that settled Madagascar followed a coastal route through South Asia and East Africa, rather than directly across the Indian Ocean.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Genetic evidence suggests that some individuals of Austronesian descent reached Africa and the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] By around the 2nd century BC, the Neolithic Austronesian jade and spice trade networks in Southeast Asia connected with the maritime trade routes of South Asia, the Middle East, eastern Africa, and the Mediterranean, becoming what is now known as the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Prior to the 10th century, the eastern part of the route was primarily used by Southeast Asian Austronesian traders using distinctive lashed-lug ships, although Tamil and Persian traders also sailed the western parts of the routes.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It allowed the exchange of goods from East and Southeast Asia on one end, all the way to Europe and eastern Africa on the other.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Srivijaya, an Austronesian polity founded at Palembang in 682 AD, rose to dominate the trade in the region around the straits of Malacca and Sunda and the South China Sea emporium by controlling the trade in luxury aromatics and Buddhist artefacts from West Asia to a thriving Tang market.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It emerged through the conquest and subjugation of neighbouring thalassocracies.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] These included Melayu, Kedah, Tarumanagara, and Mataram, among others.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] These polities controlled the sea lanes in Southeast Asia and exploited the spice trade of the Spice Islands, as well as maritime trade-routes between India and China.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Chinese civilisation that emerged within the Yellow River valley is one of earliest civilisations in the world.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Prior to the formation of civilisation, neolithic cultures such as the Longshan and Yangshao dating to 5000 BC produced sophisticated pottery, cultivated millet, and likely produced clothes woven from hemp and silk.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Rice was also farmed and pigs and water buffalo were kept for food.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Longshan potters may have used the pottery wheel to produce their wares.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Chinese traditions described three ancient dynasties that predated the unification under the Qin and Han dynasties.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] These were the Xia, the Shang, and the Zhou.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] It was not until the later 20th century that many historians considered the Shang or Xia to be anything other than legendary.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Little is yet known about the Xia, which appears to have begun around 2200 BC, and may have controlled parts of the Yangtze River valley.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Shang dynasty traditionally is dated to 1766 to 1122 BC.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Bronze was central to Shang culture and technology, with chariots and bronze weapons helping to expand Shang control over northern China.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The cities at Ao and Yinxu, near Anyang, have been excavated and city walls, royal palaces, and archives as well as tombs and workshops were found.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] A system of writing developed, beginning with oracle bones, of which over 100,000 are still extant.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Towards the end of the 2nd millennium BC, the Shang were overrun by the Zhou dynasty from the Wei River valley to the west.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Zhou rulers at this time invoked the concept of the Mandate of Heaven to legitimize their rule, a concept that would be influential for almost every successive dynasty.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] The Zhou initially established their capital in the west near modern Xi'an, near the Yellow River, but they would preside over a series of expansions into the Yangtze River valley.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] Zhou administration was decentralised, with local elites responsible for collecting tribute and providing military support to the Zhou rulers.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] In the 8th century BC, power became decentralized during the Spring and Autumn period, named after the influential *Spring and Autumn Annals*.
[src:ancient-history/ancient-history-p02] In this period, local military leaders used by the Zhou began to assert their power and vie for hegemony.
